"Shoji J., Toshito S.-I., Mizuno K.-I., Kamimura Y., Hori M., Hirakawa K.","Possible effects of global warming on fish recruitment: Shifts in spawning season and latitudinal distribution can alter growth of fish early life stages through changes in daylength",2011,"ICES Journal of Marine Science","68","6",,"1165","1169",,,10.1093/icesjms/fsr059,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959529865&partnerID=40&md5=fc3ff0ce3314cd82b91f9e34e5b32a5b","Takehara Fisheries Research Laboratory, 5-8-1 Minato-machi, Takehara, Hiroshima 725-0024, Japan; National Research Institute of Fisheries and Environment of Inland Sea, Fisheries Research Agency, 2-17-5 Maruishi, Hatsukaichi, Hiroshima 739-0452, Japan; Hiroshima Prefecture Sea-farming Center, Takasaki, Takehara, Hiroshima 729-2313, Japan","Shoji, J., Takehara Fisheries Research Laboratory, 5-8-1 Minato-machi, Takehara, Hiroshima 725-0024, Japan; Toshito, S.-I., Takehara Fisheries Research Laboratory, 5-8-1 Minato-machi, Takehara, Hiroshima 725-0024, Japan; Mizuno, K.-I., Takehara Fisheries Research Laboratory, 5-8-1 Minato-machi, Takehara, Hiroshima 725-0024, Japan; Kamimura, Y., Takehara Fisheries Research Laboratory, 5-8-1 Minato-machi, Takehara, Hiroshima 725-0024, Japan; Hori, M., National Research Institute of Fisheries and Environment of Inland Sea, Fisheries Research Agency, 2-17-5 Maruishi, Hatsukaichi, Hiroshima 739-0452, Japan; Hirakawa, K., Hiroshima Prefecture Sea-farming Center, Takasaki, Takehara, Hiroshima 729-2313, Japan","Changes in growth rates, shifts in the spawning season, and shifts in the spawning area (latitude) are expected after an increase in sea temperature resulting from global warming. Fish can avoid higher temperatures by a poleward shift in the spawning area and a temporal shift in spawning timing. However, these shifts will include changes in daylength experienced during their early life stages. To understand comprehensively the possible effects of global warming on fish recruitment, effects of temperature and daylength on growth, daily ration, and growth efficiency of black rockfish, Sebastes cheni, a dominant species in coastal waters of the western North Pacific, were examined under wild and laboratory conditions. The growth rate was elevated at higher temperatures between 11.1 and 21.3°C. Growth efficiency was highest at 16°C. The effect of photoperiod on growth was also significant, with enhanced growth resulting from the longer daylength. The effect of shifts in spawning season and spawning area would differ among fish species and spawning season. Comparison of early growth under different daylength conditions between S. cheni and ayu, Plecoglossus altivelis altivelis, indicated that the shifts in spawning season and spawning area would have different effects on fish early life stages (FELSs) related to changes in daylength. Changes in daylength resulting from a poleward shift in the spawning area will have opposite effects for summer- and winter-growing FELSs, and the effects are more prominent at higher latitudes. © 2011 International Council for the Exploration of the Sea.","daylength; fish early life stages; global warming; growth; temperature","coastal water; day length; dominance; fish; global warming; growth rate; latitude; photoperiod; population distribution; recruitment (population dynamics); seasonal variation; spawning; temperature effect; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (Northwest); Plecoglossus altivelis; Plecoglossus altivelis altivelis; Sebastes; Sebastes melanops",,,,,,"Boehlert, G.W., The effects of photoperiod and temperature on laboratory growth of juvenile Sebastes diploproa and a comparison with growth in the field (1981) Fishery Bulletin US, 79, pp. 789-794; Campana, S.E., How reliable are growth back-calculations based on otoliths? (1990) Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences, 47, pp. 2219-2227; Chesney, E.J., Estimating the food requirements of striped bass larvae Morone saxatilis: Effects of light, 